Overview

This project is a proof-of-concept (POC) to analyze friction in the mobile account opening journey across three critical failure layers:

Access Failures → Infrastructure issues (latency, retries, server load)
Maker-Checker Breakdowns → Control/process failures
CBS Posting Failures → Core banking/system-level failures

The objective is to identify key drivers of failure, quantify operational friction, and build an analytics framework relevant for BFSI roles in operations, product analytics, and consulting.

Objectives
Diagnose failure patterns across system layers
Build hypothesis-driven analytical models
Quantify impact of infrastructure and process inefficiencies
Enable early warning signals for operational failures
Demonstrate end-to-end analytics thinking (data → model → insight)

Analytical Approach
1. Hypothesis-Driven Modeling

Instead of blind modeling, the project follows structured hypotheses:

H1 (Access Layer): Failures driven by latency, retries, and peak load
(Next: Workflow and CBS layers to be modeled similarly)
2. Data Engineering
Synthetic dataset (~99K rows) designed to mimic BFSI transaction logs
Feature groups:
Infrastructure: latency, retries, server region
Behavioral: hour band, peak flags
System signals: API latency bands, sync risk
3. Modeling Strategy
Logistic Regression (baseline interpretability)
Random Forest (non-linear patterns)
Gradient Boosting (ensemble learning)

Key techniques applied:

Stratified train/validation/test split
Class imbalance awareness
Threshold tuning (F1 / PR-AUC driven)
Leakage control via feature isolation
4. Signal Engineering (Critical Step)

Initial models showed no predictive power (AUC ~0.5) → indicated weak signal.

Resolved by:

Log-odds (logit) based target generation
Strong primary drivers (latency)
Interaction effects (latency × peak hour)
Controlled stochastic noise
